# DebugProgress for Algorithm Output

> Codex mirror: `docs/rules/debug-progress.md` — keep both in sync.

All optimizer and solver **algorithm telemetry** must go through `DebugProgress`, not direct `std::cerr`.

## Required pattern

Obtain the reporter from `OptimizerContext` (or `DebugProgress::from_environment()` in `Solver`):

```cpp
DebugProgress& debug = context.debug_progress;

debug.log([&](std::ostream& os) {
    os << "MyOptimizer: baseline score = " << score << '\n';
});

debug.report_if_due(elapsed, best_metrics, baseline_metrics, current_score);
```

## Do not

```cpp
// ❌ Direct stderr for algorithm progress/summary
std::cerr << "MyOptimizer: best score = " << best_score << '\n';
```

## When to use each API

- **`debug.log(...)`** — phase transitions, baseline/warmup/final summaries, batch completion lines.
- **`debug.report_if_due(...)`** — periodic progress during long loops (prefix `Progress` on stderr).

## Gating behavior

- **Release** (`NDEBUG`): always silent.
- **Debug**: enabled only when `CADD0040_DEBUG_PROGRESS=1`; interval via `CADD0040_DEBUG_PROGRESS_INTERVAL` (default 30s).

## Allowed direct `std::cerr`

- Fatal/user-facing errors in `main.cpp` or `Solver::run()` catch blocks.
- Implementation inside `debug_progress.cpp` itself.

Low-level library failures (e.g. `ClockTree::insert_buffer`) should not add new algorithm telemetry; follow existing call-site conventions.
